
We start with a cube. This bracket just keeps confirming it's still there —
cheap, and it never duplicates.
  [let block = browser_3d.cube(1.2, 1.2, 1.2, "gray")]

It spins forever, using the shared TIME namespace directly. No wrapper needed
here — the whole bracket already re-runs every tick.
  [browser_3d.rotate(block, TIME.t * 15, TIME.t * 20, 0)]

Here's a circle that keeps growing on its own too. This one DOES need a
wrapper function, specifically on the radius: Paper.js can't resize a circle
after it's built, so a plain number here would only ever set the fixed
starting size — wrapping it is what reaches the mechanism that keeps the
growth going.
  [let c1 = browser_2d.circle(() => 50 + TIME.t, "red")]

This next shape swaps from a circle to a square at ten seconds, in the very
same slot, with nothing left behind.
  [let maker = (TIME.t > 10 ? browser_2d.square : browser_2d.circle); let shape = maker(80, "lime", 400, 400)]

Watch this one ease between two spots every five seconds — it only restarts
the ease when the target actually changes, not every frame.
  [browser_2d.move(c1, (Math.floor(TIME.t / 5) % 2 === 0 ? 200 : 700), 300, 1)]

One bracket, both worlds at once: a new circle appears here, while the cube's
opacity pulses over there.
  [let flash = browser_2d.circle(30, "cyan", 900, 900); browser_3d.opacity(block, 0.5 + 0.5 * Math.sin(TIME.t * 3))]

Both worlds react to the microphone — this only needs to run once, since it
manages its own ongoing pulse from here.
  [!browser_2d.audio_reactive(c1, 0.8, 1.3)] [!browser_3d.audio_reactive(block, 0.8, 1.3)]

That's everything. Clean slate — a one-time action, not something to leave
running.
  [!browser_2d.clear(); browser_3d.clear()]

